$summary = 'District administration and police held a consultation with marriage hall owners in Coimbatore on March 17, 2026, directing them not to allow premises to be used for distribution of cash or gifts during the election period.';

$content = <<<'HTML'
<p class="lead">The district administration and police held a consultation meeting with marriage hall owners in Coimbatore on March 17, 2026, and directed them not to allow their premises to be used for distribution of cash, gifts or other inducements during the Tamil Nadu Assembly election period. Officials said the advisory was issued to plug a route through which unaccounted benefits could reach voters under the guise of social functions, and to strengthen enforcement of the Model Code of Conduct ahead of polling.</p>

<p>Marriage halls and kalyanamandapams are central to social life in Coimbatore, hosting weddings, receptions and family events throughout the year. During election season, such venues occasionally double as informal gathering points for supporters of candidates, and enforcement agencies have in the past flagged instances where functions were used to distribute money or valuables. The March 17 meeting brought together representatives of major halls across the city and suburbs to align on expectations and reporting procedures. Attendance was described as strong, with several owners travelling from Singanallur, Ukkadam and Saravanampatti to hear the guidelines first-hand.</p>

<p>The city's cosmopolitan character—with communities from across Tamil Nadu, Kerala and other states celebrating diverse wedding rituals—means that peak seasons vary. Temple festival weeks and auspicious muhurtham dates already strain parking and crowd management; adding election surveillance without disturbing guests requires coordination that officials acknowledged would test managers' skills. Templates for communicating the new rules to clients via SMS and email were shared at the meeting so that families booking halls could be briefed even before they arrived at the venue.</p>

<p>The District Collector, senior police officers and election nodal officers addressed the gathering. They explained that any attempt to use a booked hall for political largesse—not merely routine hospitality at a genuine wedding—could attract action under election law and could lead to cancellation of licences or police cases against both organisers and property owners. Owners were asked to verify the purpose of bookings during the election window and to inform the nearest police station if they suspected misuse. A question-and-answer session ran for nearly forty minutes, with owners raising doubts about dual events and shared parking lots used by adjacent banquet facilities.</p>

<h2>Why marriage halls matter for poll enforcement</h2>

<p>Flying squads and static surveillance teams focus on roads and public spaces, but indoor venues can be harder to monitor without cooperation from property owners. Marriage halls often have multiple entry points, private parking and long hours of operation, which can make discreet distribution of cash or gifts harder to detect from outside. By bringing owners into the compliance chain, the administration hopes to close a gap that political operatives might otherwise exploit.</p>

<p>Officials cited precedents from other districts where election authorities had acted against venues that knowingly allowed platform speeches coupled with distribution of envelopes or goods to attendees who were not necessarily family guests. The line between legitimate wedding customs and electoral inducement can be thin; the advisory errs on the side of caution during the Model Code period. In one widely discussed case from another southern district, a reception had doubled as a campaign rally; the hall licence was suspended pending inquiry. Coimbatore officers said they hoped awareness would prevent similar situations here.</p>

<p>Women's self-help groups and resident associations that often book community halls for smaller functions were encouraged to apply the same principles even when the scale was modest. Any gathering that morphs into a ward-level political meeting without proper permission could expose organisers and venue providers to scrutiny.</p>

<p>Hall owners said they welcomed clarity on what was expected. Several representatives pointed out that most bookings in the coming weeks were genuine weddings fixed months in advance, and that they did not want their properties dragged into controversy. They requested a single helpline or WhatsApp channel to report suspicious last-minute changes to guest lists or programme schedules that might indicate political use.</p>

<h2>What owners were asked to do</h2>

<p>Among the directions: maintain a register of bookings with contact details of the primary organiser; flag any sudden additions of parallel events such as "public meetings" or "felicitations" tagged to a political figure on the same day; refuse split bookings where one part of the hall is ostensibly for a wedding and another for a political gathering without clear authorisation; and cooperate with flying squads if they seek entry for inspection based on complaints.</p>

<p>Owners were also told not to accept cash payments without proper receipts for large advances during this period, as opaque transactions could later be linked to electoral spending. Digital payments and named invoices were encouraged. For community halls run by trusts, office-bearers were asked to pass resolutions endorsing compliance and to display notices at entrances that distribution of cash or gifts for electoral purposes is prohibited.</p>

<p>Police said patrolling near major marriage hubs would be intensified on weekends and auspicious days when wedding volume peaks. They asked owners to keep security staff briefed so that entry checks—already common at larger halls for safety—could be coordinated with election teams without causing panic among genuine guests. Sub-inspectors attached to each assembly segment have been given lists of large halls so that beat officers can make quick spot visits if the control room relays a tip.</p>

<p>In neighbourhoods such as Town Hall, Gandhipuram and Ramanathapuram, where several halls stand within a few hundred metres of each other, cluster coordinators from the revenue department have been named to liaise with multiple properties on the same day. That arrangement is meant to avoid duplication of inspections and to ensure that if one venue raises an alert, adjacent ones can be sensitised without delay.</p>

<h2>Model Code and legal backdrop</h2>

<p>The Model Code of Conduct bars parties and candidates from offering inducements to voters. While marriage-related gifts among families are social customs, using a wedding as a cover for voter bribery violates the spirit and letter of the code. The Election Commission has in past circulars asked district authorities to sensitise managers of banquet halls, community centres and places of worship.</p>

<p>Penalties can range from seizure of distributed items and FIRs under relevant sections of the Indian Penal Code and Representation of the People Act to administrative action against commercial properties. Candidates' expenditure accounts must reflect legitimate costs; unreported spending channelled through third-party venues can lead to disqualification proceedings if proved. Repeat violations in the same establishment could invite stricter scrutiny in future licensing cycles.</p>

<p>Legal aid volunteers present at the meeting briefly explained that hall owners were not expected to police politics but to exercise reasonable diligence—much like a landlord's responsibility to avoid knowingly abetting an offence on their premises. They distributed a one-page FAQ in Tamil and English summarising the advisory, contact numbers for the election helpline, and the steps to take if an organiser pressured a manager to overlook suspicious activity.</p>

<p>Childcare and senior citizens' safety at crowded weddings remained a parallel concern: owners were reminded that emergency exits must stay clear even if extra crowds gather, and that sound levels should stay within permitted decibel limits so that complaints do not divert police bandwidth during a high-alert fortnight.</p>

<h2>Reactions from the trade</h2>

<p>Representatives of the marriage hall associations in RS Puram, Peelamedu and Sai Baba Colony said bookings for April and May remained strong and that they would comply with the advisory. Some smaller venues on the outskirts expressed concern about verifying the intent behind every booking, given thin staff strength. Officials responded that proportionate due diligence—such as confirming identity for bulk cash advances—would suffice and that good-faith operators would not be penalised for isolated oversights. A few owners requested police patrolling near isolated halls after late-night events; the administration noted the request for deployment planning.</p>

<p>Catering contractors and event managers who often work the same circuit were informally asked to spread the word so that parallel arrangements—such as car parks where cash might change hands—could also be watched. The district machinery has been coordinating across departments so that messaging is consistent. Photographers and videographers were also nudged to decline requests to stage political banners or cut-outs that could turn a private event into a campaign backdrop without authorisation.</p>

<p>Hotel banquet wings attached to star properties fall under a similar advisory, though Monday's meeting focused on standalone marriage halls that form the bulk of middle-class celebrations in Coimbatore. Industry insiders estimated that more than 200 significant venues operate across the corporation limits, with another cluster in the peripheral panchayats where oversight can be lighter—precisely why outreach was described as urgent.</p>

<h2>For families planning weddings</h2>

<p>Officials stressed that genuine weddings need not be postponed. Customs such as return gifts within family budgets are not the target. The focus is on organised distribution tied to electoral mobilisation. Families were advised to keep documentation for any large expenditures that might be questioned if complaints arise, and to avoid scheduling political photo-ops at the same venue on polling eve.</p>

<p>Brides' and grooms' families that have already paid advances said they did not expect disruption. Hall managers indicated that existing contracts would be honoured, with an additional clause acknowledgement where needed for compliance with the election advisory. Wedding planners who coordinate décor, music and guest logistics said they would brief their teams to avoid last-minute political branding that could embarrass hosts or attract flying squads.</p>

<p>Insurance brokers who offer event-liability covers noted that policies might exclude losses arising from government-ordered closures tied to unlawful activity; organisers were advised to read fine print if they purchased add-ons for high-value weddings during the poll window.</p>

<h2>What happens next</h2>

<p>The district control room will track complaints related to marriage halls. cVIGIL and other election apps can be used to report suspected misuse. Flying squads may inspect premises if credible information is received. A follow-up meeting may be held if enforcement feedback suggests gaps.</p>

<p>As polling day approaches, the administration has asked hall owners to remain vigilant in the final fortnight when last-minute bookings sometimes spike. Cooperation from the sector, officials said, would go a long way toward ensuring that Coimbatore's reputation for orderly conduct of both elections and social life is maintained. The Collector's office has promised weekly bulletins summarising complaints and resolutions so that associations can track trends.</p>

<p>Observers from the Election Commission who monitor campaign expenditure may also seek sample invoices from high-footfall venues if specific candidates' spending patterns raise questions. Transparency in billing, managers were told, protects both the business and the client.</p>

<p>City residents who book smaller mandapams for betrothals and cradle ceremonies said they appreciated the administration spelling out expectations early rather than leaving managers to interpret vague warnings. Social media chatter in local groups reflected cautious optimism that the advisory would deter a few bad actors without casting a shadow over ordinary celebrations.</p>

<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

<h3>Can I still hold my wedding during the election period?</h3>
<p>Yes. Genuine weddings are allowed. The advisory targets misuse of halls for distributing cash or gifts to influence votes, not legitimate family functions.</p>

<h3>What should I do if a political party asks to use our hall for a rally?</h3>
<p>Political events are governed by separate permissions from police and election authorities. Marriage halls should ensure any such event has valid approval and is not a cover for inducement. When in doubt, contact the local police or the district election office.</p>

<h3>Will police enter our hall without notice?</h3>
<p>Inspections usually follow complaints or specific intelligence. Cooperation with flying squads when they identify themselves is expected. Owners can ask for identity verification of personnel.</p>

<h3>Who pays if a booking is cancelled due to suspicion of misuse?</h3>
<p>That depends on contract terms between the organiser and the hall. Owners were advised to include compliance clauses in agreements during the election period to reduce disputes.</p>

<h3>Does this apply to temples and community mandapams?</h3>
<p>Similar principles apply wherever gatherings can be used for inducement. Temple trusts and community bodies were being reached through separate channels; marriage hall owners were asked to coordinate with them if events spanned multiple venues.</p>

<h3>Where can I report pressure from a political worker?</h3>
<p>Use the district control room number, the Election Commission helpline, or cVIGIL. Anonymous complaints are accepted though follow-up may be easier if contact details are shared.</p>
